aa(lp14
VSo when I was growing up
p15
aVin a really rural area in Maine,
p16
aVthe Internet meant something very different to me.
p17
aVIt meant a connection to the world.
p18
aVIt meant something that would connect us all together.
p19
aVAnd I was sure that it was going to be great for democracy
p20
aVand for our society.
p21
aVBut there's this shift
p22
aVin how information is flowing online,
p23
aVand it's invisible.
p24
aVAnd if we don't pay attention to it,
p25
aVit could be a real problem.
p26
aVSo I first noticed this in a place I spend a lot of time \u2014
p27
aVmy Facebook page.
p28
aVI'm progressive, politically \u2014 big surprise \u2014
p29
aVbut I've always gone out of my way to meet conservatives.
p30
aVI like hearing what they're thinking about;
p31
aVI like seeing what they link to;
p32
aVI like learning a thing or two.
p33
aVAnd so I was surprised when I noticed one day
p34
aVthat the conservatives had disappeared from my Facebook feed.
p35
aVAnd what it turned out was going on
p36
aVwas that Facebook was looking at which links I clicked on,
p37
aVand it was noticing that, actually,
p38
aVI was clicking more on my liberal friends' links
p39
aVthan on my conservative friends' links.
p40
aVAnd without consulting me about it,
p41
aVit had edited them out.
p42
aVThey disappeared.
p43
aa(lp44
VSo Facebook isn't the only place
p45
aVthat's doing this kind of invisible, algorithmic
p46
aVediting of the Web.
p47
aVGoogle's doing it too.
p48
aVIf I search for something, and you search for something,
p49
aVeven right now at the very same time,
p50
aVwe may get very different search results.
p51
aVEven if you're logged out, one engineer told me,
p52
aVthere are 57 signals
p53
aVthat Google looks at \u2014
p54
aVeverything from what kind of computer you're on
p55
aVto what kind of browser you're using
p56
aVto where you're located \u2014
p57
aVthat it uses to personally tailor your query results.
p58
aVThink about it for a second:
p59
aVthere is no standard Google anymore.
p60
aVAnd you know, the funny thing about this is that it's hard to see.
p61
aVYou can't see how different your search results are
p62
aVfrom anyone else's.
p63
aa(lp64
VBut a couple of weeks ago,
p65
aVI asked a bunch of friends to Google "Egypt"
p66
aVand to send me screen shots of what they got.
p67
aVSo here's my friend Scott's screen shot.
p68
aVAnd here's my friend Daniel's screen shot.
p69
aVWhen you put them side-by-side,
p70
aVyou don't even have to read the links
p71
aVto see how different these two pages are.
p72
aVBut when you do read the links,
p73
aVit's really quite remarkable.
p74
aVDaniel didn't get anything about the protests in Egypt at all
p75
aVin his first page of Google results.
p76
aVScott's results were full of them.
p77
aVAnd this was the big story of the day at that time.
p78
aVThat's how different these results are becoming.
