aa(lp96
VSo I do think this is a problem.
p97
aVAnd I think, if you take all of these filters together,
p98
aVyou take all these algorithms,
p99
aVyou get what I call a filter bubble.
p100
aVAnd your filter bubble is your own personal,
p101
aVunique universe of information
p102
aVthat you live in online.
p103
aVAnd what's in your filter bubble
p104
aVdepends on who you are, and it depends on what you do.
p105
aVBut the thing is that you don't decide what gets in.
p106
aVAnd more importantly,
p107
aVyou don't actually see what gets edited out.
p108
aVSo one of the problems with the filter bubble
p109
aVwas discovered by some researchers at Netflix.
p110
aVAnd they were looking at the Netflix queues, and they noticed something kind of funny
p111
aVthat a lot of us probably have noticed,
p112
aVwhich is there are some movies
p113
aVthat just sort of zip right up and out to our houses.
p114
aVThey enter the queue, they just zip right out.
p115
aVSo "Iron Man" zips right out,
p116
aVand "Waiting for Superman"
p117
aVcan wait for a really long time.
p118
aa(lp119
VWhat they discovered
p120
aVwas that in our Netflix queues
p121
aVthere's this epic struggle going on
p122
aVbetween our future aspirational selves
p123
aVand our more impulsive present selves.
p124
aVYou know we all want to be someone
p125
aVwho has watched "Rashomon,"
p126
aVbut right now
p127
aVwe want to watch "Ace Ventura" for the fourth time.
p128
aV(Laughter)
p129
aVSo the best editing gives us a bit of both.
p130
aVIt gives us a little bit of Justin Bieber
p131
aVand a little bit of Afghanistan.
p132
aVIt gives us some information vegetables;
p133
aVit gives us some information dessert.
p134
aVAnd the challenge with these kinds of algorithmic filters,
p135
aVthese personalized filters,
p136
aVis that, because they're mainly looking
p137
aVat what you click on first,
p138
aVit can throw off that balance.
p139
aVAnd instead of a balanced information diet,
p140
aVyou can end up surrounded
p141
aVby information junk food.
p142
aa(lp143
VWhat this suggests
p144
aVis actually that we may have the story about the Internet wrong.
p145
aVIn a broadcast society \u2014
p146
aVthis is how the founding mythology goes \u2014
p147
aVin a broadcast society,
p148
aVthere were these gatekeepers, the editors,
p149
aVand they controlled the flows of information.
p150
aVAnd along came the Internet and it swept them out of the way,
p151
aVand it allowed all of us to connect together,
p152
aVand it was awesome.
p153
aVBut that's not actually what's happening right now.
p154
aVWhat we're seeing is more of a passing of the torch
p155
aVfrom human gatekeepers
p156
aVto algorithmic ones.
p157
aVAnd the thing is that the algorithms
p158
aVdon't yet have the kind of embedded ethics
p159
aVthat the editors did.
p160
aVSo if algorithms are going to curate the world for us,
p161
aVif they're going to decide what we get to see and what we don't get to see,
p162
aVthen we need to make sure
p163
aVthat they're not just keyed to relevance.
p164
aVWe need to make sure that they also show us things
p165
aVthat are uncomfortable or challenging or important \u2014
p166
aVthis is what TED does \u2014
p167
aVother points of view.
p168
aa(lp169
VAnd the thing is, we've actually been here before
p170
aVas a society.
p171
aVIn 1915, it's not like newspapers were sweating a lot
p172
aVabout their civic responsibilities.
p173
aVThen people noticed
p174
aVthat they were doing something really important.
p175
aVThat, in fact, you couldn't have
p176
aVa functioning democracy
p177
aVif citizens didn't get a good flow of information,
p178
aVthat the newspapers were critical because they were acting as the filter,
p179
aVand then journalistic ethics developed.
p180
aVIt wasn't perfect,
p181
aVbut it got us through the last century.
p182
aVAnd so now,
p183
aVwe're kind of back in 1915 on the Web.
p184
aVAnd we need the new gatekeepers
p185
aVto encode that kind of responsibility
p186
aVinto the code that they're writing.
p187
aa(lp188
VI know that there are a lot of people here from Facebook and from Google \u2014
p189
aVLarry and Sergey \u2014
p190
aVpeople who have helped build the Web as it is,
p191
aVand I'm grateful for that.
